  "business_context": "Document records anchor file management in CRMs: signed contracts, proposals, presentations, ID documents, photos, screenshots, audit files, transcripts, recorded calls, and any other binary content that needs to live alongside structured data. Modern CRMs split file management from the rest of the data model into a dedicated content layer (Salesforce ContentVersion / ContentDocument; HubSpot Files; Attio attachments) — partly because file storage has different access patterns (large objects, lazy load, download URLs) than structured data, partly because version history matters for documents but not most other records. CiviCRM has Attachment via core File entity attached polymorphically. Bloomerang has Documents on Constituents. EspoCRM has Document (with version tracking). The key operational concerns are storage limits (most systems cap file size at 25-100MB), supported MIME types, virus scanning, and external-storage integrations (Google Drive, Dropbox, S3) that let the CRM reference a file without storing it directly. When interviewing clients, surface \"Document\" by asking what files they attach to records (signed forms, photos, IDs, contracts), how they currently store them, and whether they need version history or external-storage integration.",
